---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Base title="Research" description="Ongoing research directions for Private Reads — PIR for Merkle trees, delegated hint generation, DEPIR, GPU-optimized schemes, and more.">
  <section class="section hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Research</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Open problems and active research directions that shape the next generation of
        privacy-preserving read protocols for Ethereum.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" style="padding-top: 0;">
    <div class="container prose">

      <h2>PIR for Merkle Trees</h2>
      <p>
        Client-side verifiability requires retrieving not just leaf values but sibling hashes
        along paths to state roots. Two baseline approaches exist:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Per-level PIR instances</strong> — maintain separate PIR databases for each tree level.
        Since trie paths are determined by keys, all per-level queries can process in parallel.
        In tries with branching factor <em>b</em> and <em>N</em> leaves, total cost across
        <em>D</em> levels is <em>b &middot; D</em> times the cost of querying a single level.
        For <a href={`${base}/workstreams/ubt`}>UBT</a> (<em>b</em> = 2, realistic upper bound <em>D</em> &approx; 40):
        total overhead is approximately 9&times;. For MPT (<em>b</em> = 16, realistic upper bound <em>D</em> &approx; 10):
        total overhead is approximately 48&times;.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Pre-attach proofs to leaves</strong> — concatenate each leaf's full Merkle proof
        into its PIR database entry. This eliminates separate queries but causes significant storage blowup:
        UBT proofs are ~1,280 bytes per leaf (40&times; blowup), MPT proofs are ~4,800 bytes per leaf (150&times; blowup).
      </p>
      <p>
        Intermediate strategies exist — pre-attaching partial proofs for top <em>k</em> levels while
        querying remaining bottom levels separately reduces both database count and per-entry blowup.
      </p>

      <h2>Verifiable UBT over MPT</h2>
      <p>
        The <a href={`${base}/workstreams/ubt`}>binary state trie</a> can be adopted today by proving
        equivalence to the canonical MPT. This reduces PIR database size for hosting Merkle roots and
        simplifies optimizations like SNARKification. The public input to the UBT state-transition prover
        is a canonical zkVM proof of the next L1 block plus the block body — block application and
        verification run within the zkVM proof of the UBT state transition function.
      </p>

      <h2>Isolating Mutability</h2>
      <p>
        Some Ethereum datasets update in an append-only fashion: blocks, blobs, and historical state
        snapshots. The approach: snapshot at fixed points (e.g., January 1st yearly), perform preprocessing
        once, and never update that dataset. Newer data maintains a dedicated, update-optimal dataset until
        it grows large enough to be immobilized with a different scheme. RPC routing based on the
        <code>blockNumber</code> parameter directs queries to the appropriate dataset.
      </p>

      <h2>SNARKifying Archival State to Reduce DB Size</h2>
      <p>
        Assuming Ethereum state uses UBT (no extension nodes, single unified trie), instead of fetching
        Merkle roots and hashing to verify historical balances, users verify a SNARK attesting validity.
        Every Ethereum block receives a zkVM proof <em>P<sub>s</sub></em>. An archival node update proof
        <em>P<sub>h</sub></em> for that block:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Verifies <em>P<sub>s</sub></em> with witness <em>W<sub>s</sub></em>, proving the link to the entire chain</li>
        <li>Applies <em>W<sub>s</sub></em> to generate the history snapshot</li>
        <li>For each touched account-header stem node, generates a Merkle path proof</li>
        <li>Updates a key-value table tracking (leaf, last_edited)</li>
        <li>Verifies the previous <em>P<sub>h&minus;1</sub></em>, creating a recursive chain of trust</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        SNARK-proving the validity of account header changes eliminates Merkle root requirements for
        balance, nonce, and codehash lookups.
      </p>

      <h2>Delegating Hint Generation in Interactive-Hint Schemes</h2>
      <p>
        Interactive-hint schemes like <a href="https://0xalizk.github.io/plinko-arch/">Plinko</a> and
        <a href="https://github.com/keewoolee/rms24">RMS24</a> achieve sublinear online server time
        but require clients to stream entire databases during hint generation. Delegating this to a
        server via FHE or MPC could reduce both computational and bandwidth burden on clients, though
        this remains prohibitively expensive with current constructions.
      </p>

      <h2>Concretely Efficient DEPIR</h2>
      <p>
        Doubly Efficient PIR (DEPIR) combines client-stateless simplicity with asymptotically sublinear
        server-side cost. However, constants in existing asymptotic bounds place current constructions
        orders of magnitude behind practical PIR schemes on real databases. Achieving concrete efficiency
        would dramatically simplify the PIR landscape: a single client-stateless scheme with sublinear
        per-query cost could serve all data slices.
      </p>

      <h2>Novel Double-Stateless GPU-Optimized Schemes</h2>
      <p>
        We are actively working on a stateless scheme (both client and server) that is tailored to GPU
        optimization. We expect to publish this with a reference implementation in Q2 2026 — potentially
        with some collaborators.
      </p>

